see that some door has been fixed in ancient zone that saw its last heavy usage back in the velious era.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think that Darkpakt hit it right on the mark. Higher Level players are already hooked on EverQuest. They're not going to leave EQ for another game, nor are they going to cancel their accounts, until they have exhausted their own patience with the genre of the game. Content and quality of content are, honestly, very secondary here. It's really the community that keeps them going - their fellow players, their guild, and so on. <br>
<br>
Newbies need content and opportunities to experience rushes of fantasy, imagination and ambition to be locked into the EverQuest cycle of never-ending timesinks. In order for this to happen, they need to gradually shift their focus back to the lower level players. <br>
<br>
To date, SOE/VI's focus on placating the uber-guilds and uber-players with Kunark, Velious, Luclin and Planes of Power, has been aimed at establishing a relatively high and quasi-unattainable (for most people, anyways) cap that newbies will drool over as they hear about it for months and years to come. When I first started playing EQ in June of 1999, Plane of Fear and Plane of Hate were both the wildest rage (not to mention the forbidden Carmine to be harvested there by wizards). That same sort of appeal has to be there, and continue to grow wilder in order to appeal to more sophisticated audiences, and to their mean population (which, previously, had been at the mid-tier levels).<br>
<br>
But, one also needs to take into consideration that pandering to the lower-levels really is not going to last long, if it has not ended already. This is because EverQuest, for most intents and purposes, has stopped growing on the basis of attracting first time players, and its developers are much more focused on keeping its current player base from leaving and going to more sophisticated games. (Shadowbane, despite its graphical limitations and early lagginess, is proving a considerable relative drain on EQ membership - as has Dark Age of Camelot.) As more competition emerges, this will only be better for the players that remain on EverQuest, because the devs will be more willing to accomodate them to keep them interested in paying their monthly subscription fees. <br>
<br>
Don't like the Planes of Power now? Wait a year or two, and they'll be as accessible as Crushbone or Blackburrow (if not through sheer in-game mechanics, then, surely by pick-up raiding or more inclusive guilding practices).<br>
<br>
In either case, the age of pandering to either the top end or the low end has concluded; SOE is wise to pursue a policy of customer retention, and this means approaching the common denominator. It is, regrettably, one of the earliest signs, on MUDs, at least, of a game's slip into back-burner status.<br>
<br>
Kaelon <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.kaelon.com/images/kaesiggy2.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
